{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505371"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:29:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:29:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2435"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2435"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.02,0.08,0.61,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2435"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54056"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2435"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2435"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39529"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"2112"},{"type":"tags","id":"2115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4101"},{"type":"tags","id":"4103"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1903"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1918"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14110"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43151"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54056"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health check-up and cervical screening test. Her periods are regular, occurring at 28-day intervals and lasting for five days with no changes to her flow. Her menarche was at age 13. Her last menstrual period was two weeks ago. She is currently sexually active with a long-term male partner, and they use barrier contraception consistently. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Her BMI is 29 kg/m\u00b2. Pelvic examination reveals a smooth and mobile left adnexal mass. A pelvic ultrasound shows a simple five-centimetre cyst (anechoic, thin and smooth-walled).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence the combined oral contraceptive pill for at least three months","Diagnostic laparoscopy","Serum CA-125 levels","Repeat ultrasound in three months","Reassurance and no further action required"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is asymptomatic with an incidental finding of a single ovarian cyst. The mass is smooth, mobile, thin-walled, and anechoic on ultrasound, suggestive of a benign simple ovarian cyst. Simple cysts appear as anechoic (black), thin-walled structures on ultrasound, while complex cysts may have internal echoes, septations, or solid components. Management of an asymptomatic premenopausal woman with a simple 5 cm ovarian cyst involves a \u003Cstrong\u003Erepeat ultrasound in approximately three months\u003C/strong\u003E. This is to monitor for any changes in the size of the cyst or identify cyst resolution. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECysts \u0026lt;5 cm that are simple and asymptomatic with no other risk factors do not require further monitoring or treatment, so \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassurance and no further action\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in this case. An ovarian cyst that is complex in nature, persisting for three months or more, larger than 7 cm, or associated with increasing symptoms warrants referral to a gynaecologist for further investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing the combined oral contraceptive pill\u003C/strong\u003E (COCP) is not the first-line management for an asymptomatic simple ovarian cyst. Research from the 1970-1990s identified an inverse relationship between use of oral contraceptives an the development of functional ovarian cysts. At that time, it was acceptable practice to prescribe the COCP for simple ovarian cysts, expecting a resulting reduction in size or resolution of the cyst. This practice has been shown to be both unnecessary and ineffective as although hormonal contraceptives may be associated with a reduction in new cyst formation, they do not consistently cause regression of existing cysts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum CA-125 levels\u003C/strong\u003E should be measured if an ovarian mass appears complex or is present in a postmenopausal woman. This test forms part of the Risk of Malignancy Index (RMI), which is used in screening for malignant tumours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ediagnostic laparoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated for a patient with pain that is not settling with analgesia or if there are concerns for ovarian torsion. However, it is not a first-line investigation for a simple ovarian cyst.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most simple ovarian cysts in young women resolve spontaneously within three months.","Simple cysts appear as anechoic, thin-walled structures on ultrasound, while complex cysts may have internal echoes, septations, or solid components."],"references":["Farghaly SA. Current diagnosis and management of ovarian cysts. Clin Exp Obstet Gynecol. 2014;41(6):609-12. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25551948/","Smith-Bindman R, Poder L, Johnson E, Miglioretti DL. Risk of Malignant Ovarian Cancer Based on Ultrasonography Findings in a Large Unselected Population. JAMA Intern Med. 2019 Jan 1;179(1):71-77. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30419104/","Biggs WS, Marks ST. Diagnosis and Management of Adnexal Masses. Am Fam Physician. 2016 Apr 15;93(8):676-81. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2016/0415/p676.html","Yeoh M. Investigation and management of an ovarian mass [Internet]. Australian Family Physician. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2015/january-february/investigation-and-management-of-an-ovarian-mass","Grimes DA, Jones LB, Lopez LM, Schulz KF. Oral contraceptives for functional ovarian cysts. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2014 Apr 29;2014(4):CD006134. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10964840/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39529"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2435"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39529"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-29T10:39:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-29T10:39:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2435"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54056"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},